==========================================================================
 DU HALL WATER TANK  -  Value Iteration vs Q-Learning
==========================================================================
 States |S| = 1584  (level 11 x hour 24 x grid 2 x diesel 3)
 Legal state-action pairs: 3432 of 4752 (PUMP_GRID needs the grid, PUMP_GEN needs diesel)
 Transition matrix nnz = 39984  (0.531% dense)
 gamma = 0.99  ->  effective horizon 1/(1-gamma) = 100 hours
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
 E1  VALUE ITERATION
     converged in 2273 sweeps (0.24 s)
     empirical contraction rate = 0.9900   (theory says exactly gamma = 0.99)
     cross-check |V* - V^pi*|_inf = 1.81e-08  (VI agrees with the exact linear solve)
     optimal value V* (mean over start states) = -163.637
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
 E2  DOES THIS PROBLEM ACTUALLY NEED LOOKAHEAD?
                                 Policy    Exact V   Regret %   Cost/day  Shortage units/day  Diesel h/day  Dry hours/day
              Value iteration (optimal)    -163.64       0.00      32.81                0.78          1.18           0.41
Tuned caretaker rule (grid<9, diesel<3)    -187.38      14.51      36.85                0.94          1.11           0.52
             Myopic greedy ($\gamma$=0)    -361.01     120.62      78.11                3.08          1.64           1.58
                 Random (legal actions)    -697.47     326.23     166.34                6.85          2.00           3.19
                            Always idle   -2507.78    1432.53     527.66               26.38          0.00          12.31

     The formally-correct greedy policy loses 121%.
     The best TUNED reactive threshold rule still loses 14.5%.
     So the lookahead is doing real work - this is not a vacuous MDP.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
 E3  LEARNING FROM EXPERIENCE  (5 seeds x 30,000 episodes x 24 h)
     done in 73 s
     state-action coverage reached: 100.0% of legal pairs
     after 720,000 steps:
       Q-learning              regret =  15.13 % +/- 2.36
       Certainty-equiv. VI     regret =   1.43 % +/- 0.23   (SAME samples)
     action-optimality of the learned Q-policy: 86.6% of states
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
 E4  HOW WRONG CAN THE PRIOR MODEL BE?
 Believed outage rate (x truth)   Regret %
                           2.00       1.54
                           1.50       0.43
                           1.25       0.11
                           1.00       0.00
                           0.75       0.24
                           0.50       1.54
                           0.35       2.10
                           0.25       2.66
                           0.10       6.66
                           0.00      21.39

     A prior model this wrong STILL beats Q-learning (15.13%): scales 0.1 .. 2.0
     Certainty-equivalence VI (1.43%, learned from 720,000 samples):
       beats a BADLY wrong prior : scales [0.0, 0.1, 0.25, 0.35, 0.5, 2.0]
       LOSES to a mildly wrong one: scales [0.75, 1.25, 1.5]
     => a roughly-right prior model is worth more than 82 simulated years
        of experience. That is the finding, and it is not the one we expected.
